# Type rules

## Semantic aliases over bare primitives

Replace bare `string` and `number` with semantic type aliases where the meaning is clear: pathname → `Pathname`, URL → `UrlString`, route params → `RouteParams`, pattern → `PathPattern`, etc. Use them in parameters, variables, return types, and type assertions.

**Examples:**

```ts
// ❌ Bad — bare string/number
function match(pathname: string): { params: Record<string, string> } { ... }
type Params = Record<string, string>;

// ✅ Good — semantic aliases (в т.ч. ключ/значение в Record)
function match(pathname: Pathname): { params: RouteParams } { ... }
type RouteParams = Record<RouteParamName, RouteParamValue>;
```

**When to add an alias:** same meaning repeated in signatures, Map/Record keys, or type fields — add type in `types.ts` with short JSDoc.

**When to keep simple:** one-off params with obvious meaning from arg name can stay `string`/`number`; interfaces mirroring external API (e.g. Navigation) may stay without aliases.
